reviews.review_text:
Great Peter Thanx to Tony for taping and making these shows possible.  I did not have this whole run.  
I flew out from FL alone for these shows.  One of the best things about going to shows alone is it opens you up to meeting so many more folks.  And I met some great ones.  I have very few memories of this show despite being completely sober.  I woke up this morning with a horrible flu.  Shivering on the floor all day wishing I wasn't so compelled to go.  Forced myself to the bus to BART to the Coliseum.  I remember thinking wow a 2nd set Cumberland and found myself hunched over on the stairs up high adjacent to the stage for most of the set wishing someone would put me to bed.  Must have been a pathetic sight.
I have had most of the show as a soundboard for a few years.  I would recommend the audience over boards on all 3 nights.  This is average sounding, loud bob but not as loud as previous 2 shows.  Phil is there but the vocals are a bit in the back and keyboards even more so.  I would recommend this only if you want every show or attended this one.  Otherwise check it out to see if it fits your taste. Notwithstanding, as any show there are some fine moments:
A romping Alabama opens but is a bit short.  I am a fan of Tons of Steel and Desolation row, so decent songs for me.  Music to close the set!
Second set opens with a good Saint, which for the only time ever segues into a rare 2nd set Cumberland, which segues into Samson the 1st of only 2 times this was played.  Nice opener.  I really like the He's Gone, a show highlight.   The Smile Smile Smile line is perfect for this run and the crowd loves it.  Nice vocal outro jams, with Jerry singing with his guitar, I loved that. Other one is real short, but I do like the quietly sung 1st verse.  The other highlight is The Peter, wow, very well sung, check out Jerry singing the "Poor is Me" line.  Bob lays in some great flourishes, except during the Come and see Chorus, you can sense the crowd rising but the guitar drowns Jerry's vocals and seems to not quite lift off as it could have.  You've heard them do the rest of the show a million times, though the NFA has way more meaning than usual given the circumstance.
I have no idea how I made it back to Pacifica this night.  Peace
